The “PROBLEM” of missing Cost of Goods (COGs)¶

Background:¶

In the development of Commercial Dashboards for Nordic Region, we discovered three problems:

  1. We identified issues in transferring Cost of Sales Information from S4 to BI/SAC. In S4 it is referred to as PCIP, see below image.

  2. An alternative method of transferring data was implemented - extracting the data directly from Material Ledger. It is IMPORTANT to note that data from Material Ledger is based on the date of the billing document and TIME RELEVANT. In the vast majority of cases the cost information has been checked and seen to be flowing through from S4 to to BI/SAC which in turn helps to inform the calculation for Margin.

  3. However, we also identified many materials where COGS is ZERO for certain time periods.

Objective:¶

The objective of this report is to identify patterns in the missing data from the downloaded information provided by BI team which covers 2022 and YTD Aug 2023:

  1. MATERIALS - which types of products are missing COGs data?
  2. PLANTS - is this specific to plants?
  3. TIME - are the issue timing related?

Actionable Insights:¶

  1. The insights from the above will help us raise awareness on the importance of implementing and following the right process. It will help us zoom in on specific plants and products areas so we can resolve them in priority order.

  2. The final section of the report will help USERS of Commercial Dashboard to understand where they need to show caution. We have provided significance using INV QTY so it is relative. Not all the data is incorrect, for example 1 Material missing COGs in one time period will not materially impact the overall metrics,

REMEMBER: WE CANNOT CORRECT THE DATA IN RETROSPECT.

Observations:¶

  • The highest Net Invoice Value for a P4 level is for Bitumen - 43653. However, there are only 14 unique materials in that category which means that individual values of Invoice Quantity is very high. A similar case is seen for category Flat Roofing Components.
  • Apart from that, Pitched Roofing Components has high volume in terms of number of materials and is also significant in terms of Invoice Quantity.

When it appears as negative invoice qty, we have potentially recorded negative sales say -100 but potentially not recorded the product cost(let’s assume 50) which means a P&L hit of -100 instead of -50.

That is not to say is what actually happened as we may have made some accounting adjustments BUT this is however it appears when looking at the data from source billing docs and cost of goods from S4 to BI(in the dashboards)
